The sell-off gathered speed at the close on Wall Street, with S&P 500 falling 12%, the Nasdaq a bit more and the Dow industrials down almost 13% on the day.
Some $2.69 trillion in market value was wiped from the S&P 500 as it suffered its third-largest percentage decline.
The S&P 500 plunged 8% at the open to trigger an automatic 15-minute trading halt on the three main U.S. stock indexes, marking the third emergency pause on Wall Street in six days.
Rate-sensitive U.S. financial stocks plunged 14.0%, leading declines among the major S&P sectors.
The S&P 500 lost 324.89 points, or 11.98%, to 2,386.13 and the Nasdaq Composite dropped 970.28 points, or 12.32%, to 6,904.59.